Remaining common consonants still allowed (not yet used): C, M, P, B, G, H, K, V, W, Y, etc.

Another balanced option with known-good letters plus two new common consonants: “PORCH” – but O is in position 2, which we know is wrong.

Instead, let’s place R, O, U in new positions and pick two high-frequency consonants: C and M.  A valid word is “CORNU” but that keeps U in 4th place, which is allowed (no prior info on 4th).  However, CORNU is obscure.

A more common word: “CRUMP” – uses C, M with R, O, U, but U is in position 3, which was already marked wrong in ROUND.

Better: move U to 1st, R to 3rd, O to 4th, and add two new consonants.  That gives U _ R O _.  Common word: “CURIO” again, but it has I.

Another high-frequency consonant pair: B and K.  Try “BROOK”: but O is in 2nd position which is disallowed.

A solid word that respects all constraints:
- Uses R, O, U
- Moves each to a new position (R≠1, O≠2, U≠3)
- Adds two new common consonants

Satisfying all: “CROUP” – C (new), R (moved to 2nd), O (moved to 3rd), U (moved to 4th), P (new).  All constraints satisfied.

So the next guess is CROUP.
</think>
